      "task": "Yes, please proceed: Solve the second-order ODE with the given initial conditions.",
      "result": "# Solving the Second-Order ODE\n\n$$\\frac{d^2V}{dt^2} + 8\\frac{dV}{dt} + 100V = 100, \\qquad V(0) = 0,\\quad V'(0) = 0$$\n\n---\n\n## Step 1 — Characteristic Equation\n\nSubstitute $V \\sim e^{rt}$:\n\n$$r^2 + 8r + 100 = 0$$\n\n---\n\n## Step 2 — Discriminant\n\n$$\\Delta = 8^2 - 4(1)(100) = 64 - 400 = -336$$\n\nSince $\\Delta < 0$, the roots are **complex conjugates** — this is an **underdamped** system.\n\n---\n\n## Step 3 — Roots\n\n$$r = \\frac{-8 \\pm \\sqrt{-336}}{2} = \\frac{-8 \\pm i\\sqrt{336}}{2} = -4 \\pm i\\sqrt{84}$$\n\nSince $\\sqrt{84} = 2\\sqrt{21}$:\n\n$$\\boxed{r = -4 \\pm 2i\\sqrt{21}}$$\n\nSo the damping coefficient is $\\alpha = 4$ and the damped natural frequency is $\\omega_d = 2\\sqrt{21} \\approx 9.165$ rad/s.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4 — Homogeneous Solution\n\n$$V_h(t) = e^{-4t}\\!\\left(C_1 \\cos(2\\sqrt{21}\\, t) + C_2 \\sin(2\\sqrt{21}\\, t)\\right)$$\n\n---\n\n## Step 5 — Particular Solution\n\nThe right-hand side is a constant, so try $V_p = A$:\n\n$$0 + 0 + 100A = 100 \\implies A = 1$$\n\n$$\\boxed{V_p = 1}$$\n\n---\n\n## Step 6 — General So"
